[src:special-functions/airy-function] In mathematics, the **Airy function** (or **Airy function of the first kind**) $\mathbf {Ai({\boldsymbol {x}})}$ is a special function named after the British astronomer George Biddell Airy.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] The function $\operatorname {Ai} (x)$ and the related function $\mathbf {Bi({\boldsymbol {x}})}$ are linearly independent solutions to the differential equation ${\frac {d^{2}y}{dx^{2}}}-xy=0,$ known as the **Airy equation** or the **Stokes equation**.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] Because the solution of the linear differential equation ${\frac {d^{2}y}{dx^{2}}}-ky=0$ is oscillatory for $k<0$ and exponential for $k>0$ , the Airy functions are oscillatory for $x<0$ and exponential for $x>0$ .
[src:special-functions/airy-function] In fact, the Airy equation is the simplest second-order linear differential equation with a turning point (a point where the character of the solutions changes from oscillatory to exponential).
[src:special-functions/airy-function] Up to scalar multiplication, $\operatorname {Ai} (x)$ is the solution subject to the condition $y\to 0$ as $x\to \infty$ .
[src:special-functions/airy-function] The standard choice for the other solution is the Airy function of the second kind, denoted $\operatorname {Bi} (x)$ .
[src:special-functions/airy-function] It follows that the Wronskian of $\operatorname {Ai} (x)$ and $\operatorname {Bi} (x)$ is $1/\pi$ .
[src:special-functions/airy-function] When x is positive, $\operatorname {Ai} (x)$ is positive, convex, and decreasing exponentially to zero, while $\operatorname {Bi} (x)$ is positive, convex, and increasing exponentially.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] When x is negative, $\operatorname {Ai} (x)$ and $\operatorname {Bi} (x)$ oscillate around zero with ever-increasing frequency and ever-decreasing amplitude as $x\to -\infty$ .
[src:special-functions/airy-function] This is supported by the asymptotic formulae below for the Airy functions.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] again using an improper Riemann integral.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] Neither $\operatorname {Ai} (x)$ nor its derivative $\operatorname {Ai} '(x)$ have positive real zeros.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] As explained below, the Airy functions can be extended to the complex plane, giving entire functions.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] The asymptotic behaviour of the Airy functions as |z| goes to infinity at a constant value of arg(*z*) depends on arg(*z*): this is called the Stokes phenomenon.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] When |arg(*z*)| = 0 these are good approximations but are not asymptotic because the ratio between Ai(−*z*) or Bi(−*z*) and the above approximation goes to infinity whenever the sine or cosine goes to zero.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] Asymptotic expansions for these limits are also available.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] These are listed in Abramowitz and Stegun (1983) and Olver (1974).
[src:special-functions/airy-function] One is also able to obtain asymptotic expressions for the derivatives Ai'(z) and Bi'(z).
[src:special-functions/airy-function] Alternatively, we can use the differential equation *y*′′ − *xy* = 0 to extend Ai(*x*) and Bi(*x*) to entire functions on the complex plane.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] The asymptotic formula for Ai(*x*) is still valid in the complex plane if the principal value of *x*2/3 is taken and x is bounded away from the negative real axis.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] The formula for Bi(*x*) is valid provided x is in the sector $x\in \mathbb {C} :\left|\arg(x)\right|<{\tfrac {\pi }{3}}-\delta$ for some positive δ.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] It follows from the asymptotic behaviour of the Airy functions that both Ai(*x*) and Bi(*x*) have an infinity of zeros on the negative real axis.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] The Scorer's functions Hi(*x*) and -Gi(*x*) solve the equation *y*′′ − *xy* = 1/π.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] As was noted earlier, it evaluates to ${\frac {1}{\pi }}$ .
[src:special-functions/airy-function] grants various integrals a closed form that would otherwise be unattainable.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] Then, $i{\hat {y}}'+k^{2}{\hat {y}}=0$ , which then has solutions ${\hat {y}}=Ce^{ik^{3}/3}.$ There is only one dimension of solutions because the Fourier transform requires y to decay to zero fast enough; Bi grows to infinity exponentially fast, so it cannot be obtained via a Fourier transform.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] The Airy function is the solution to the time-independent Schrödinger equation for a particle confined within a triangular potential well and for a particle in a one-dimensional constant force field.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] For the same reason, it also serves to provide uniform semiclassical approximations near a turning point in the WKB approximation, when the potential may be locally approximated by a linear function of position.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] The triangular potential well solution is directly relevant for the understanding of electrons trapped in semiconductor heterojunctions.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] A transversally asymmetric optical beam, where the electric field profile is given by the Airy function, has the interesting property that its maximum intensity *accelerates* towards one side instead of propagating in a straight line as is the case in symmetric beams.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] This is at expense of the low-intensity tail being spread in the opposite direction, so the overall momentum of the beam is of course conserved.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] The Airy function underlies the form of the intensity near an optical directional caustic, such as that of the rainbow (called supernumerary rainbow).
[src:special-functions/airy-function] Historically, this was the mathematical problem that led Airy to develop this special function.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] In 1841, William Hallowes Miller experimentally measured the analog to supernumerary rainbow by shining light through a thin cylinder of water, then observing through a telescope.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] The Airy function is the universal local model near a fold caustic (in semiclassical optics).
[src:special-functions/airy-function] The phase shift by $\pi /4$ in the asymptotic expansion of $\operatorname {Ai} (-x)$ is the local form of the Maslov phase correction, which globally is encoded by the Maslov index.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] In the mid-1980s, the Airy function was found to be intimately connected to Chernoff's distribution.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] The Airy function also appears in the definition of Tracy–Widom distribution which describes the law of largest eigenvalues in Random matrix.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] Due to the intimate connection of random matrix theory with the Kardar–Parisi–Zhang equation, there are central processes constructed in KPZ such as the Airy process.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] The Airy function is named after the British astronomer and physicist George Biddell Airy (1801–1892), who encountered it in his early study of optics in physics.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] The notation Ai(*x*) was introduced by Harold Jeffreys.
[src:special-functions/airy-function] Airy had become the British Astronomer Royal in 1835, and he held that post until his retirement in 1881.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Bessel functions are solutions to a particular type of ordinary differential equation: $x^{2}{\frac {d^{2}y}{dx^{2}}}+x{\frac {dy}{dx}}+\left(x^{2}-\alpha ^{2}\right)y=0,$ where $\alpha$ is a number that determines the shape of the solution.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] This number is called the *order* of the Bessel function and can be any complex number.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Although the same equation arises for both $\alpha$ and $-\alpha$ , mathematicians define separate Bessel functions for each to ensure the functions behave smoothly as the order changes.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The most important cases are when $\alpha$ is an integer or a half-integer.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] When $\alpha$ is an integer, the resulting Bessel functions are often called **cylinder functions** or **cylindrical harmonics** because they naturally arise when solving problems (like Laplace's equation) in cylindrical coordinates.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] When $\alpha$ is a half-integer, the solutions are called **spherical Bessel functions** and are used in spherical systems, such as in solving the Helmholtz equation in spherical coordinates.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Bessel's equation arises when finding separable solutions to Laplace's equation and the Helmholtz equation in cylindrical or spherical coordinates.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Bessel functions are therefore especially important for many problems of wave propagation and static potentials.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] In solving problems in cylindrical coordinate systems, one obtains Bessel functions of integer order ( $\alpha =n$ ); in spherical problems, one obtains half-integer orders ( $\alpha =n+1/2$ ).
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Bessel functions also appear in other fields, such as signal processing (e.g., see FM audio synthesis, Kaiser window, or Bessel filter).
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] They also appear in pure mathematics as part of the Fourier expansion of Maass forms.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Because this is a linear differential equation, solutions can be scaled to any amplitude.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The amplitudes chosen for the functions originate from the early work in which the functions appeared as solutions to definite integrals rather than solutions to differential equations.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Because the differential equation is second-order, there must be two linearly independent solutions: one of the first kind and one of the second kind.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Depending upon the circumstances, however, various formulations of these solutions are convenient.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Different variations are summarized in the table below and described in the following sections.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The subscript *n* is typically used in place of $\alpha$ when $\alpha$ is known to be an integer.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Bessel functions of the second kind and the spherical Bessel functions of the second kind are sometimes denoted by Nn and nn, respectively, rather than Yn and yn.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Bessel functions of the first kind, denoted as *Jα*(*x*), are solutions of Bessel's differential equation.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] For integer or positive α, Bessel functions of the first kind are finite at the origin (*x* = 0); while for negative non-integer α, Bessel functions of the first kind diverge as x approaches zero.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Some earlier authors define the Bessel function of the first kind differently, essentially without the division by 2 in $x/2$ ; this definition is not used in this article.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The Bessel function of the first kind is an entire function if α is an integer, otherwise it is a multivalued function with singularity at zero.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The graphs of Bessel functions look roughly like oscillating sine or cosine functions that decay proportionally to $x^{-{1}/{2}}$ (see also their asymptotic forms below), although their roots are not generally periodic, except asymptotically for large x.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] For non-integer α, the functions *Jα*(*x*) and *J*−*α*(*x*) are linearly independent, and are therefore the two solutions of the differential equation.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] This means that the two solutions are no longer linearly independent.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] In this case, the second linearly independent solution is then found to be the Bessel function of the second kind, as discussed below.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] This was the approach that Bessel used, and from this definition he derived several properties of the function.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] This expression is related to the development of Bessel functions in terms of the Bessel–Clifford function.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The Bessel functions of the second kind, denoted by *Yα*(*x*), occasionally denoted instead by *Nα*(*x*), are solutions of the Bessel differential equation that have a singularity at the origin (*x* = 0) and are multivalued.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] These are sometimes called **Weber functions**, as they were introduced by H.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Weber (1873), and also **Neumann functions** after Carl Neumann.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Both *Jα*(*x*) and *Yα*(*x*) are holomorphic functions of x on the complex plane cut along the negative real axis.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] When α is an integer, the Bessel functions J are entire functions of x.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] If x is held fixed at a non-zero value, then the Bessel functions are entire functions of α.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The Bessel functions of the second kind, when α is an integer, are an example of the second kind of solution in Fuchs's theorem.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] These linear combinations are also known as **Bessel functions of the third kind**; they are two linearly independent solutions of Bessel's differential equation.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] These forms of linear combination satisfy numerous simple-looking properties, like asymptotic formulae or integral representations.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Here, "simple" means an appearance of a factor of the form *e**i* *f*(x).
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] For real $x>0$ where $J_{\alpha }(x)$ , $Y_{\alpha }(x)$ are real-valued, the Bessel functions of the first and second kind are the real and imaginary parts, respectively, of the first Hankel function and the real and negative imaginary parts of the second Hankel function.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Thus, the above formulae are analogs of Euler's formula, substituting *H*(1) *α*(*x*), *H*(2) *α*(*x*) for $e^{\pm ix}$ and $J_{\alpha }(x)$ , $Y_{\alpha }(x)$ for $\cos(x)$ , $\sin(x)$ , as explicitly shown in the asymptotic expansion.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The Hankel functions are used to express outward- and inward-propagating cylindrical-wave solutions of the cylindrical wave equation, respectively (or vice versa, depending on the sign convention for the frequency).
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] If α is an integer, the limit has to be calculated.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] These are useful in developing the spherical Bessel functions (see below).
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The Bessel functions are valid even for complex arguments x, and an important special case is that of a purely imaginary argument.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] When α is an integer, then the limit is used.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] These are chosen to be real-valued for real and positive arguments x.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The series expansion for *Iα*(*x*) is thus similar to that for *Jα*(*x*), but without the alternating (−1)*m* factor.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] given that the condition Re(*x*) > 0 is met.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Unlike the ordinary Bessel functions, which are oscillating as functions of a real argument, Iα and Kα are exponentially growing and decaying functions respectively.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Like the ordinary Bessel function Jα, the function Iα goes to zero at *x* = 0 for *α* > 0 and is finite at *x* = 0 for *α* = 0.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Analogously, Kα diverges at *x* = 0 with the singularity being of logarithmic type for K0, and ⁠1/2⁠Γ(|*α*|)(2/*x*)|*α*| otherwise.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Bessel functions can be described as Fourier transforms of powers of quadratic functions.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] It can be proven by showing equality to the above integral definition for *K*0.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] This is done by integrating a closed curve in the first quadrant of the complex plane.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The modified Bessel function $K_{\frac {1}{2}}(\xi )=(2\xi /\pi )^{-1/2}\exp(-\xi )$ is useful to represent the Laplace distribution as an Exponential-scale mixture of normal distributions.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] yn is also denoted nn or ηn; some authors call these functions the **spherical Neumann functions**.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The zeroth spherical Bessel function *j*0(*x*) is also known as the (unnormalized) sinc function.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] There are simple closed-form expressions for the Bessel functions of half-integer order in terms of the standard trigonometric functions, and therefore for the spherical Bessel functions.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The spherical Hankel functions appear in problems involving spherical wave propagation, for example in the multipole expansion of the electromagnetic field.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] For example, this kind of differential equation appears in quantum mechanics while solving the radial component of the Schrödinger equation with hypothetical cylindrical infinite potential barrier.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] This differential equation, and the Riccati–Bessel solutions, also arises in the problem of scattering of electromagnetic waves by a sphere, known as Mie scattering after the first published solution by Mie (1908).
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] See e.g., Du (2004) for recent developments and references.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Following Debye (1909), the notation ψn, χn is sometimes used instead of Sn, Cn.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The Bessel functions have the following asymptotic forms.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] For the second case (where $\alpha$ is a positive integer) one term will dominate unless $\alpha$ is imaginary.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] For large real arguments *z* ≫ |*α*2 − ⁠1/4⁠|, one cannot write a true asymptotic form for Bessel functions of the first and second kind (unless α is half-integer) because they have zeros all the way out to infinity, which would have to be matched exactly by any asymptotic expansion.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] It is interesting that although the Bessel function of the first kind is the average of the two Hankel functions, *Jα*(*z*) is not asymptotic to the average of these two asymptotic forms when z is negative (because one or the other will not be correct there, depending on the arg *z* used).
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] These formulas can be used to determine a recurrence relation for $J_{\alpha }(x)$ , a more general form of which is given below.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] For integer order *α* = *n*, Jn is often defined via a Laurent series for a generating function: $e^{{\frac {x}{2}}\left(t-{\frac {1}{t}}\right)}=\sum _{n=-\infty }^{\infty }J_{n}(x)t^{n}$ an approach used by P.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Infinite series of Bessel functions in the form ${\textstyle \sum _{\nu =-\infty }^{\infty }J_{N\nu +p}(x)}$ where $\nu ,p\in \mathbb {Z} ,\ N\in \mathbb {Z} ^{+}$ arise in many physical systems and are defined in closed form by the Sung series.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The latter is equivalent to $e^{\pm iz\sin \phi }=J_{0}(z)+2\sum _{n=1}^{\infty }J_{2n}(z)\cos(2n\phi )\pm 2i\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }J_{2n+1}(z)\sin((2n+1)\phi )$ which is used to expand a plane wave as a sum of cylindrical waves, or to find the Fourier series of a tone-modulated FM signal.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] This formula is useful especially when working with Fourier transforms.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Because Bessel's equation becomes Hermitian (self-adjoint) if it is divided by x, the solutions must satisfy an orthogonality relationship for appropriate boundary conditions.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] This orthogonality relation can then be used to extract the coefficients in the Fourier–Bessel series, where a function is expanded in the basis of the functions *Jα*(*x* *u**α*,*m*) for fixed α and varying m.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Conversely, the Hankel transform (of the same order) of *gε*(*k*) is *fε*(*x*): $\int _{0}^{\infty }kJ_{\alpha }(kx)g_{\varepsilon }(k)\,dk=f_{\varepsilon }(x)$ which is zero everywhere except near 1.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] As ε approaches zero, the right-hand side approaches *δ*(*x* − 1), where δ is the Dirac delta function.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] For *α* > −1, the even entire function of genus 1, *x*−*α**Jα*(*x*), has only real zeros.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] These two identities are often combined, e.g. added or subtracted, to yield various other relations.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] In this way, for example, one can compute Bessel functions of higher orders (or higher derivatives) given the values at lower orders (or lower derivatives).
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] These recurrence relations are useful for discrete diffusion problems.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] In 1929, Carl Ludwig Siegel proved that *J**ν*(*x*), *J*'*ν*(*x*), and the logarithmic derivative ⁠*J*'*ν*(*x*)/*J**ν*(*x*)⁠ are transcendental numbers when *ν* is rational and *x* is algebraic and nonzero.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The same proof also implies that $\Gamma (v+1)(2/x)^{v}J_{v}(x)$ is transcendental under the same assumptions.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] These sums can be extended to include a term multiplier that is a polynomial function of the index.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The Bessel functions obey a multiplication theorem $\lambda ^{-\nu }J_{\nu }(\lambda z)=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }{\frac {1}{n!}}\left({\frac {\left(1-\lambda ^{2}\right)z}{2}}\right)^{n}J_{\nu +n}(z),$ where λ and ν may be taken as arbitrary complex numbers.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] For |*λ*2 − 1| < 1, the above expression also holds if J is replaced by Y.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Bessel himself originally proved that for nonnegative integers n, the equation *J**n*(*x*) = 0 has an infinite number of solutions in x.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] When the functions *J**n*(*x*) are plotted on the same graph, though, none of the zeros seem to coincide for different values of n except for the zero at *x* = 0.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] This phenomenon is known as **Bourget's hypothesis** after the 19th-century French mathematician who studied Bessel functions.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Specifically it states that for any integers *n* ≥ 0 and *m* ≥ 1, the functions *Jn*(*x*) and *J**n* + *m*(*x*) have no common zeros other than the one at *x* = 0.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The hypothesis was proved by Carl Ludwig Siegel in 1929.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Siegel proved in 1929 that when *ν* is rational, all nonzero roots of *J**ν*(x) and *J*'*ν*(x) are transcendental, as are all the roots of *K**ν*(x).
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] For numerical studies about the zeros of the Bessel function, see Gil, Segura & Temme (2007), Kravanja et al.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The first appearance of a Bessel function appears in the work of Daniel Bernoulli in 1732, while working on the analysis of a vibrating string, a problem that was tackled before by his father Johann Bernoulli.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Daniel considered a flexible chain suspended from a fixed point above and free at its lower end.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] The solution of the differential equation led to the introduction of a function that is now considered $J_{0}(x)$ .
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Bernoulli also developed a method to find the zeros of the function.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Leonhard Euler in 1736, found a link between other functions (now known as Laguerre polynomials) and Bernoulli's solution.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Euler also introduced a non-uniform chain that led to the introduction of functions now related to modified Bessel functions $I_{n}(x)$ .
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] In the middle of the eighteen century, Jean le Rond d'Alembert had found a formula to solve the wave equation.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] By 1771 there was dispute between Bernoulli, Euler, d'Alembert and Joseph-Louis Lagrange on the nature of the solutions of vibrating strings.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Euler worked in 1778 on buckling, introducing the concept of Euler's critical load.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] To solve the problem he introduced the series for $J_{\pm 1/3}(x)$ .
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Euler also worked out the solutions of vibrating 2D membranes in cylindrical coordinates in 1780.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] In order to solve his differential equation he introduced a power series associated to $J_{n}(x)$ , for integer *n*.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] During the end of the 18th century Lagrange, Pierre-Simon Laplace and Marc-Antoine Parseval also found equivalents to the Bessel functions.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Parseval, for example, found an integral representation of $J_{0}(x)$ using cosine.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] At the beginning of the 1800s, Joseph Fourier used $J_{0}(x)$ to solve the heat equation in a problem with cylindrical symmetry.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Fourier won a prize of the French Academy of Sciences for this work in 1811.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] But most of the details of his work, including the use of a Fourier series, remained unpublished until 1822.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Poisson, in rivalry with Fourier, extended Fourier's work in 1823, introducing new properties of Bessel functions, including Bessel functions of half-integer order (now known as spherical Bessel functions).
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] In 1770, Lagrange introduced the series expansion of Bessel functions to solve Kepler's equation, a transcendental equation in astronomy.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Friedrich Wilhelm Bessel had seen Lagrange's solution but found it difficult to handle.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] In 1813 in a letter to Carl Friedrich Gauss, Bessel simplified the calculation using trigonometric functions.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] Bessel published his work in 1819, independently introducing the method of Fourier series unaware of the work of Fourier which was published later.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] In 1824, Bessel carried out a systematic investigation of the functions, which earned the functions his name.
[src:special-functions/bessel-function] In older literature the functions were called cylindrical functions or even Bessel–Fourier functions.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] In mathematics, the **beta function**, also called the Euler integral of the first kind, is a special function that is closely related to the gamma function and to binomial coefficients.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] The beta function was studied by Leonhard Euler and Adrien-Marie Legendre and was given its name by Jacques Binet; its symbol Β is a Greek capital beta.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] A proof is given below in § Relationship to the gamma function.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] The beta function is also closely related to binomial coefficients.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] To derive this relation, write the product of two factorials as integrals.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] Changing variables by *u* = *st* and *v* = *s*(1 − *t*), because *u + v* = *s* and *u* / (*u*+*v*) = *t*, we have that the limits of integrations for *s* are 0 to ∞ and the limits of integration for *t* are 0 to 1.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] Dividing both sides by $\Gamma (z_{1}+z_{2})$ gives the desired result.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] The stated identity may be seen as a particular case of the identity for the integral of a convolution.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] See *The Gamma Function*, page 18–19 for a derivation of this relation.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] where $\psi (z)$ denotes the digamma function.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] where in the second-to-last identity n is any positive real number.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] One may move from the first integral to the second one by substituting $t=\tan ^{2}(\theta )$ .
[src:special-functions/beta-function] This Pochhammer contour integral converges for all values of α and β and so gives the analytic continuation of the beta function.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] For *x* = 1, the incomplete beta function coincides with the complete beta function.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] For positive integers *a* and *b*, the incomplete beta function will be a polynomial of degree *a* + *b* − 1 with rational coefficients.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] The $4m$ and $4m+1$ convergents are less than $\mathrm {B} (x;\,a,b)$ , while the $4m+2$ and $4m+3$ convergents are greater than $\mathrm {B} (x;\,a,b)$ .
[src:special-functions/beta-function] This multivariate beta function is used in the definition of the Dirichlet distribution.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] Its relationship to the beta function is analogous to the relationship between multinomial coefficients and binomial coefficients.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] The beta function is useful in computing and representing the scattering amplitude for Regge trajectories.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] Furthermore, it was the first known scattering amplitude in string theory, first conjectured by Gabriele Veneziano.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] It also occurs in the theory of the preferential attachment process, a type of stochastic urn process.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] The beta function is also important in statistics, e.g. for the beta distribution and beta prime distribution.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] As briefly alluded to previously, the beta function is closely tied with the gamma function and plays an important role in calculus.
[src:special-functions/beta-function] Even if unavailable directly, the complete and incomplete beta function values can be calculated using functions commonly included in spreadsheet or computer algebra systems.
