[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] In mathematics, the **gamma function** (represented by ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠, capital Greek letter gamma) is the most common extension of the factorial function to complex numbers.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] First studied by Daniel Bernoulli, the gamma function $\Gamma (z)$ is defined for all complex numbers z except non-positive integers, and $\Gamma (n)=(n-1)!$ for every positive integer ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Since the gamma function has no zeros, its reciprocal ${\frac {1}{\Gamma }}$ is an entire function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Other extensions of the factorial function do exist, but the gamma function is the most popular and useful.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] It appears as a factor in various probability-distribution functions and other formulas in the fields of probability, statistics, analytic number theory, and combinatorics.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The gamma function can be seen as a solution to the interpolation problem of finding a smooth curve $y=f(x)$ that connects the points of the factorial sequence: $(x,y)=(n,n!)$ for all positive integer values of ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The simple formula for the factorial, $x!=1\cdot 2\cdot 3\cdots x$ is only valid when x is a positive integer, and no elementary function has this property, but a good solution is the gamma function ⁠ $f(x)=\Gamma (x+1)$ ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The gamma function is not only smooth but analytic (except at the non-positive integers), and it can be defined in several explicit ways.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] However, it is not the only analytic function that extends the factorial, as one may add any analytic function that is zero on the positive integers, such as $k\sin(m\pi x)$ for an integer ⁠ m ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Such a function is known as a pseudogamma function, the most famous being the Hadamard function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] But this still does not give a unique solution, since it allows for multiplication by any periodic function $g(x)$ with $g(x)=g(x+1)$ and ⁠ $g(0)=1$ ⁠, such as ⁠ $g(x)=e^{k\sin(m\pi x)}$ ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] One way to resolve the ambiguity is the Bohr–Mollerup theorem, which shows that $f(x)=\Gamma (x)$ is the unique interpolating function for the factorial, defined over the positive reals, which is logarithmically convex, meaning that $y=\log f(x)$ is convex.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The notation $\Gamma (z)$ is due to Legendre.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] If the real part of the complex number z is strictly positive (⁠ $\Re (z)>0$ ⁠), then the integral $\Gamma (z)=\int _{0}^{\infty }t^{z-1}e^{-t}\,dt$ converges absolutely, and is known as the **Euler integral of the second kind**.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Thus we have shown that $\Gamma (n)=(n-1)!$ for any positive integer n by induction.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The identity ${\textstyle z\Gamma (z)=\Gamma (z+1)}$ can be used (or, yielding the same result, analytic continuation can be used) to uniquely extend the integral formulation for $\Gamma (z)$ to a meromorphic function defined for all complex numbers ⁠ z ⁠, except integers less than or equal to zero.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] It is this extended version that is commonly referred to as the gamma function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] If m is not an integer then this equation is meaningless since, in this section, the factorial of a non-integer has not been defined yet.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] In fact, the above assumption produces a unique definition of $\Gamma (z)$ as ⁠ $(z-1)!$ ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The infinite product for the reciprocal ${\frac {1}{\Gamma (z)}}=z\prod _{n=1}^{\infty }\left[\left(1+{\frac {z}{n}}\right)/{\left(1+{\frac {1}{n}}\right)^{z}}\right]$ is an entire function, converging for every complex number ⁠ z ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The definition for the gamma function due to Weierstrass is also valid for all complex numbers z except non-positive integers: $\Gamma (z)={\frac {e^{-\gamma z}}{z}}\prod _{n=1}^{\infty }\left(1+{\frac {z}{n}}\right)^{-1}e^{z/n},$ where $\gamma \approx 0.577216$ is the Euler–Mascheroni constant.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] This is the Hadamard product of $\textstyle {\frac {1}{\Gamma (z)}}$ in a rewritten form.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The duplication formula is a special case of the multiplication theorem (see Eq.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] See Particular values of the gamma function for calculated values.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] However, these numbers $\Gamma (r)$ are not known to be expressible by themselves in terms of elementary functions.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] In general, when computing values of the gamma function, we must settle for numerical approximations.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] When restricted to the positive real numbers, the gamma function is a strictly logarithmically convex function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The last of these statements is, essentially by definition, the same as the statement that ⁠ $\psi ^{(1)}(x)>0$ ⁠, where $\psi ^{(1)}$ is the polygamma function of order 1.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] To prove the logarithmic convexity of the gamma function, it therefore suffices to observe that $\psi ^{(1)}$ has a series representation which, for positive real x, consists of only positive terms.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] There are also bounds on ratios of gamma functions.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] This growth is faster than exponential, ⁠ $\exp(\beta x)$ ⁠, for any fixed value of ⁠ $\beta$ ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The behavior for non-positive z is more intricate.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Euler's integral does not converge for ⁠ $\Re (z)\leq 0$ ⁠, but the function it defines in the positive complex half-plane has a unique analytic continuation to the negative half-plane.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] One way to find that analytic continuation is to use Euler's integral for positive arguments and extend the domain to negative numbers by repeated application of the recurrence formula, $\Gamma (z)={\frac {\Gamma (z+n+1)}{z(z+1)\cdots (z+n)}},$ choosing n such that $z+n$ is positive.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The product in the denominator is zero when z equals any of the integers ⁠ $0,-1,-2,\ldots$ ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Thus, the gamma function must be undefined at those points to avoid division by zero; it is a meromorphic function with simple poles at the non-positive integers.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] There is in fact no complex number z for which ⁠ $\Gamma (z)=0$ ⁠, and hence the reciprocal gamma function ${\textstyle {\dfrac {1}{\Gamma (z)}}}$ is an entire function, with zeros at ⁠ $z=0,-1,-2,\ldots$ ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The gamma function rises to either side of this minimum.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The gamma function must alternate sign between its poles at the non-positive integers because the product in the forward recurrence contains an odd number of negative factors if the number of poles between z and $z+n$ is odd, and an even number if the number of poles is even.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] There are many formulas, besides the Euler integral of the second kind, that express the gamma function as an integral.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Let C be a Hankel contour, meaning a path that begins and ends at the point ∞ on the Riemann sphere, whose unit tangent vector converges to −1 at the start of the path and to 1 at the end, which has winding number 1 around 0, and which does not cross ⁠ $[0,\infty )$ ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Fix a branch of $\log(-t)$ by taking a branch cut along $[0,\infty )$ and by taking $\log(-t)$ to be real when t is on the negative real axis.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The reflection formula leads to the closely related expression ${\frac {1}{\Gamma (z)}}={\frac {i}{2\pi }}\int _{C}(-t)^{-z}e^{-t}\,dt,$ which is valid whenever ⁠ $z\not \in \mathbb {Z}$ ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] However, Iaroslav Blagouchine discovered that Carl Johan Malmsten first derived this series in 1842.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The latter can be derived taking the logarithm in the above multiplication formula, which gives an expression for the Riemann sum of the integrand.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Taking the limit for $a\to \infty$ gives the formula.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] An alternative notation introduced by Gauss is the $\Pi$ -function, a shifted version of the gamma function: $\Pi (z)=\Gamma (z+1)=z\Gamma (z)=\int _{0}^{\infty }e^{-t}t^{z}\,dt,$ so that $\Pi (n)=n!$ for every non-negative integer ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The shifted reciprocal gamma function is sometimes denoted ⁠ $\pi (z)={\frac {1}{\Pi (z)}}$ ⁠, an entire function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The values presented here are truncated rather than rounded.) The complex-valued gamma function is undefined for non-positive integers, but in these cases the value can be defined in the Riemann sphere as ⁠ $\infty$ ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Because the gamma and factorial functions grow so rapidly for moderately large arguments, many computing environments include a function that returns the natural logarithm of the gamma function, often given the name `lgamma` or `lngamma` in programming environments or `gammaln` in spreadsheets.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] This grows much more slowly, and for combinatorial calculations allows adding and subtracting logarithmic values instead of multiplying and dividing very large values.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The digamma function, which is the derivative of this function, is also commonly seen.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] is often used since it allows one to determine function values in one strip of width 1 in z from the neighbouring strip.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] In particular, starting with a good approximation for a z with large real part one may go step by step down to the desired ⁠ z ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The coefficients of the terms with $k>1$ of $z^{1-k}$ in the last expansion are simply ${\frac {B_{k}}{k(k-1)}},$ where the $B_{k}$ are the Bernoulli numbers.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The Bohr–Mollerup theorem states that among all functions extending the factorial functions to the positive real numbers, only the gamma function is log-convex, that is, its natural logarithm is convex on the positive real axis.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Another characterisation is given by the Wielandt theorem.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] In a certain sense, the log-gamma function is the more natural form; it makes some intrinsic attributes of the function clearer.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] A striking example is the Taylor series of logΓ around 1: $\operatorname {log\Gamma } (z+1)=-\gamma z+\sum _{k=2}^{\infty }{\frac {\zeta (k)}{k}}\,(-z)^{k}\qquad \forall \;|z|<1$ with ⁠ $\zeta (k)$ ⁠ denoting the Riemann zeta function at ⁠ k ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] There also exist special formulas for the logarithm of the gamma function for rational ⁠ z ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] When $z=1$ it follows that $\int _{0}^{1}\operatorname {log\Gamma } (x)\,dx={\frac {1}{2}}\log(2\pi ),$ and this is a consequence of Raabe's formula as well.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Bailey and his co-authors gave an evaluation for $L_{n}:=\int _{0}^{1}\log ^{n}\Gamma (x)\,dx$ when $n=1,2$ in terms of the Tornheim–Witten zeta function and its derivatives.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] The gamma function can be computed to fixed precision for $\Re (z)\in [1,2]$ by applying integration by parts to Euler's integral.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] When ⁠ $\Re (z)\in [1,2]$ ⁠ and ⁠ $x\geq 1$ ⁠, the absolute value of the last integral is smaller than ⁠ $(x+1)e^{-x}$ ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] By choosing a large enough ⁠ x ⁠, this last expression can be made smaller than $2^{-N}$ for any desired value ⁠ N ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Thus, the gamma function can be evaluated to N bits of precision with the above series.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] A fast algorithm for calculation of the Euler gamma function for any algebraic argument (including rational) was constructed by E.A.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] For arguments that are integer multiples of ⁠ ${\tfrac {1}{24}}$ ⁠, the gamma function can also be evaluated quickly using arithmetic–geometric mean iterations (see particular values of the gamma function).
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Unlike many other functions, such as a normal distribution, no obvious fast, accurate implementation that is easy to implement for the gamma function $\Gamma (z)$ is easily found.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Therefore, it is worth investigating potential solutions.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] For the case that speed is more important than accuracy, published tables for $\Gamma (z)$ are easily found in an Internet search, such as the Online Wiley Library.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Such tables may be used with linear interpolation.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] Greater accuracy is obtainable with the use of cubic interpolation at the cost of more computational overhead.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] If interpolation tables are not desirable, then the Lanczos approximation mentioned above works well for 1 to 2 digits of accuracy for small, commonly used values of ⁠ z ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p01] If the Lanczos approximation is not sufficiently accurate, the Stirling's formula for the Gamma Function may be used.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] One author describes the gamma function as "Arguably, the most common special function, or the least 'special' of them.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The other transcendental functions [...] are called 'special' because you could conceivably avoid some of them by staying away from many specialized mathematical topics.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The gamma function finds application in such diverse areas as quantum physics, astrophysics and fluid dynamics.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The gamma distribution, which is formulated in terms of the gamma function, is used in statistics to model a wide range of processes; for example, the time between occurrences of earthquakes.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The primary reason for the gamma function's usefulness in such contexts is the prevalence of expressions of the type ⁠ $f(t)e^{-g(t)}$ ⁠, which describe processes that decay exponentially in time or space.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Integrals of such expressions can occasionally be solved in terms of the gamma function when no elementary solution exists.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The fact that the integration is performed along the entire positive real line might signify that the gamma function describes the cumulation of a time-dependent process that continues indefinitely, or the value might be the total of a distribution in an infinite space.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] It is of course frequently useful to take limits of integration other than 0 and $\infty$ to describe the cumulation of a finite process, in which case the ordinary gamma function is no longer a solution; the solution is then called an incomplete gamma function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] An important category of exponentially decaying functions is that of Gaussian functions $ae^{-{\frac {(x-b)^{2}}{c^{2}}}}$ and integrals thereof, such as the error function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] There are many interrelations between these functions and the gamma function; notably, the factor ${\sqrt {\pi }}$ obtained by evaluating ${\textstyle \Gamma \left({\frac {1}{2}}\right)}$ is the "same" as that found in the normalizing factor of the error function and the normal distribution.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The integrals discussed so far involve transcendental functions, but the gamma function also arises from integrals of purely algebraic functions.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] In particular, the arc lengths of ellipses and of the lemniscate, which are curves defined by algebraic equations, are given by elliptic integrals that in special cases can be evaluated in terms of the gamma function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The gamma function can also be used to calculate "volume" and "area" of n -dimensional hyperspheres.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The gamma function's ability to generalize factorial products immediately leads to applications in many areas of mathematics; in combinatorics, and by extension in areas such as probability theory and the calculation of power series.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Many expressions involving products of successive integers can be written as some combination of factorials, the most important example perhaps being that of the binomial coefficient.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The example of binomial coefficients motivates why the properties of the gamma function when extended to negative numbers are natural.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] A binomial coefficient gives the number of ways to choose k elements from a set of n elements; if ⁠ $k>n$ ⁠, there are of course no ways.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] If ⁠ $k>n$ ⁠, then $(n-k)!$ is the factorial of a negative integer and hence infinite if we use the gamma function definition of factorials—dividing by infinity gives the expected value of ⁠ 0 ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] We can replace the factorial by a gamma function to extend any such formula to the complex numbers.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Generally, this works for any product wherein each factor is a rational function of the index variable, by factoring the rational function into linear expressions.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] If we have a way to calculate the gamma function numerically, it is very simple to calculate numerical values of such products.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The number of gamma functions in the right-hand side depends only on the degree of the polynomials, so it does not matter whether $b-a$ equals 5 or 105.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] By taking the appropriate limits, the equation can also be made to hold even when the left-hand product contains zeros or poles.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] By taking limits, certain rational products with infinitely many factors can be evaluated in terms of the gamma function as well.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Due to the Weierstrass factorization theorem, analytic functions can be written as infinite products, and these can sometimes be represented as finite products or quotients of the gamma function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] We have already seen one striking example: the reflection formula essentially represents the sine function as the product of two gamma functions.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Starting from this formula, the exponential function as well as all the trigonometric and hyperbolic functions can be expressed in terms of the gamma function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] More functions yet, including the hypergeometric function and special cases thereof, can be represented by means of complex contour integrals of products and quotients of the gamma function, called Mellin–Barnes integrals.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] An application of the gamma function is the study of the Riemann zeta function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Among other things, this provides an explicit form for the analytic continuation of the zeta function to a meromorphic function in the complex plane and leads to an immediate proof that the zeta function has infinitely many so-called "trivial" zeros on the real line.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The gamma function has caught the interest of some of the most prominent mathematicians of all time.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Its history, notably documented by Philip J.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Davis in an article that won him the 1963 Chauvenet Prize, reflects many of the major developments within mathematics since the 18th century.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] In the words of Davis, "each generation has found something of interest to say about the gamma function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The problem of extending the factorial to non-integer arguments was apparently first considered by Daniel Bernoulli and Christian Goldbach in the 1720s.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] In particular, in a letter from Bernoulli to Goldbach dated 6 October 1729 Bernoulli introduced the product representation $x!=\lim _{n\to \infty }\left(n+1+{\frac {x}{2}}\right)^{x-1}\prod _{k=1}^{n}{\frac {k+1}{k+x}},$ which is well defined for real values of x other than the negative integers.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] He wrote to Goldbach again on 8 January 1730, to announce his discovery of the integral representation $n!=\int _{0}^{1}(-\log s)^{n}\,ds,$ which is valid when the real part of the complex number ⁠ n ⁠ is strictly greater than $-1$ (i.e., ⁠ $\Re (n)>-1$ ⁠).
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] By the change of variables ⁠ $t=-\ln s$ ⁠, this becomes the familiar Euler integral.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Euler published his results in the paper "De progressionibus transcendentibus seu quarum termini generales algebraice dari nequeunt" ("On transcendental progressions, that is, those whose general terms cannot be given algebraically"), submitted to the St.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Euler further discovered some of the gamma function's important functional properties, including the reflection formula.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] James Stirling, a contemporary of Euler, also attempted to find a continuous expression for the factorial and came up with what is now known as Stirling's formula.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Although Stirling's formula gives a good estimate of ⁠ $n!$ ⁠, also for non-integers, it does not provide the exact value.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Extensions of his formula that correct the error were given by Stirling himself and by Jacques Philippe Marie Binet.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Carl Friedrich Gauss rewrote Euler's product as $\Gamma (z)=\lim _{m\to \infty }{\frac {m^{z}m!}{z(z+1)(z+2)\cdots (z+m)}}$ and used this formula to discover new properties of the gamma function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Although Euler was a pioneer in the theory of complex variables, he does not appear to have considered the factorial of a complex number, as instead Gauss first did.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Gauss also proved the multiplication theorem of the gamma function and investigated the connection between the gamma function and elliptic integrals.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Karl Weierstrass further established the role of the gamma function in complex analysis, starting from yet another product representation, $\Gamma (z)={\frac {e^{-\gamma z}}{z}}\prod _{k=1}^{\infty }\left(1+{\frac {z}{k}}\right)^{-1}e^{\frac {z}{k}},$ where $\gamma$ is the Euler–Mascheroni constant.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Weierstrass originally wrote his product as one for ⁠ $\textstyle {\frac {1}{\Gamma }}$ ⁠, in which case it is taken over the function's zeros rather than its poles.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Inspired by this result, he proved what is known as the Weierstrass factorization theorem—that any entire function can be written as a product over its zeros in the complex plane; a generalization of the fundamental theorem of algebra.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The name gamma function and the symbol $\Gamma$ were introduced by Adrien-Marie Legendre around 1811; Legendre also rewrote Euler's integral definition in its modern form.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Although the symbol is an upper-case Greek gamma, there is no accepted standard for whether the function name should be written "gamma function" or "Gamma function" (some authors simply write "⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠-function").
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The alternative "pi function" notation $\Pi (z)=z!$ due to Gauss is sometimes encountered in older literature, but Legendre's notation is dominant in modern works.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] It is justified to ask why we distinguish between the "ordinary factorial" and the gamma function by using distinct symbols, and particularly why the gamma function should be normalized to $\Gamma (n+1)=n!$ instead of simply using ⁠ $\Gamma (n)=n!$ ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Consider that the notation for exponents, ⁠ $x^{n}$ ⁠, has been generalized from integers to complex numbers $x^{z}$ without any change.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Legendre's motivation for the normalization is not known, and has been criticized as cumbersome by some (the 20th-century mathematician Cornelius Lanczos, for example, called it "void of any rationality" and would instead use ⁠ $z!$ ⁠).
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Legendre's normalization does simplify some formulae, but complicates others.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] From a modern point of view, the Legendre normalization of the gamma function is the integral of the additive character $e^{-x}$ against the multiplicative character $x^{z}$ with respect to the Haar measure ${\textstyle {\frac {dx}{x}}}$ on the Lie group ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{+}$ ⁠.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Thus this normalization makes it clearer that the gamma function is a continuous analogue of a Gauss sum.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] It is somewhat problematic that a large number of definitions have been given for the gamma function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Although they describe the same function, it is not entirely straightforward to prove the equivalence.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Stirling never proved that his extended formula corresponds exactly to Euler's gamma function; a proof was first given by Charles Hermite in 1900.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Instead of finding a specialized proof for each formula, it would be desirable to have a general method of identifying the gamma function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] One way to prove equivalence would be to find a differential equation that characterizes the gamma function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Most special functions in applied mathematics arise as solutions to differential equations, whose solutions are unique.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] However, the gamma function does not appear to satisfy any simple differential equation.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Otto Hölder proved in 1887 that the gamma function at least does not satisfy any *algebraic* differential equation by showing that a solution to such an equation could not satisfy the gamma function's recurrence formula, making it a transcendentally transcendental function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] This result is known as Hölder's theorem.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] A definite and generally applicable characterization of the gamma function was not given until 1922.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The Bohr–Mollerup theorem is useful because it is relatively easy to prove logarithmic convexity for any of the different formulas used to define the gamma function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Taking things further, instead of defining the gamma function by any particular formula, we can choose the conditions of the Bohr–Mollerup theorem as the definition, and then pick any formula we like that satisfies the conditions as a starting point for studying the gamma function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] This approach was used by the Bourbaki group.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Borwein & Corless review three centuries of work on the gamma function.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Although the gamma function can be calculated virtually as easily as any mathematically simpler function with a modern computer—even with a programmable pocket calculator—this was of course not always the case.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Until the mid-20th century, mathematicians relied on hand-made tables; in the case of the gamma function, notably a table computed by Gauss in 1813 and one computed by Legendre in 1825.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Tables of complex values of the gamma function, as well as hand-drawn graphs, were given in *Tables of Functions With Formulas and Curves* by Jahnke and Emde, first published in Germany in 1909.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] There was in fact little practical need for anything but real values of the gamma function until the 1930s, when applications for the complex gamma function were discovered in theoretical physics.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] As electronic computers became available for the production of tables in the 1950s, several extensive tables for the complex gamma function were published to meet the demand, including a table accurate to 12 decimal places from the U.S.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Double-precision floating-point implementations of the gamma function and its logarithm are now available in most scientific computing software and special functions libraries, for example TK Solver, Matlab, GNU Octave, and the GNU Scientific Library.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] The gamma function was also added to the C standard library (math.h).
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] Arbitrary-precision implementations are available in most computer algebra systems, such as Mathematica and Maple.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] PARI/GP, MPFR and MPFUN contain free arbitrary-precision implementations.
[src:special-functions/gamma-function-p02] In some software calculators, such the Windows Calculator and GNOME Calculator, the factorial function returns $\Gamma (x+1)$ when the input x is a non-integer value.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] In mathematics, the Gaussian or ordinary **hypergeometric function** 2*F*1(*a*, *b*; *c*; *z*) is a special function represented by the **hypergeometric series**, that includes many other special functions as specific or limiting cases.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] It is a solution of a second-order linear ordinary differential equation (ODE).
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Every second-order linear ODE with three regular singular points can be transformed into this equation.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] For systematic lists of some of the many thousands of published identities involving the hypergeometric function, see the reference works by Erdélyi et al.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] There is no known system for organizing all of the identities; indeed, there is no known algorithm that can generate all identities; a number of different algorithms are known that generate different series of identities.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The theory of the algorithmic discovery of identities remains an active research topic.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The term "hypergeometric series" was first used by John Wallis in his 1655 book *Arithmetica Infinitorum*.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Hypergeometric series were studied by Leonhard Euler, but the first full systematic treatment was given by Carl Friedrich Gauss (1813).
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Studies in the nineteenth century included those of Ernst Kummer (1836), and the fundamental characterisation by Bernhard Riemann (1857) of the hypergeometric function by means of the differential equation it satisfies.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Riemann showed that the second-order differential equation for 2*F*1(*z*), examined in the complex plane, could be characterised (on the Riemann sphere) by its three regular singularities.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The cases where the solutions are algebraic functions were found by Hermann Schwarz (Schwarz's list).
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] It is undefined (or infinite) if c equals a non-positive integer.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] For complex arguments z with |*z*| ≥ 1 it can be analytically continued along any path in the complex plane that avoids the branch points 1 and infinity.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] In practice, most computer implementations of the hypergeometric function adopt a branch cut along the line *z* ≥ 1.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] As *c* → −*m*, where m is a non-negative integer, one has 2*F*1(*z*) → ∞.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] 2*F*1(*z*) is the most common type of generalized hypergeometric series pFq.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Many of the common mathematical functions can be expressed in terms of the hypergeometric function, or as limiting cases of it.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] This function can be considered as a generalization of the geometric series.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] so all functions that are essentially special cases of it, such as Bessel functions, can be expressed as limits of hypergeometric functions.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] These include most of the commonly used functions of mathematical physics.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Other polynomials that are special cases include Krawtchouk polynomials, Meixner polynomials, Meixner–Pollaczek polynomials.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The j-invariant, a modular function, is a rational function in $\lambda (\tau )$ .
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] which has three regular singular points: 0,1 and ∞.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The generalization of this equation to three arbitrary regular singular points is given by Riemann's differential equation.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Any second order linear differential equation with three regular singular points can be converted to the hypergeometric differential equation by a change of variables.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Solutions to the hypergeometric differential equation are built out of the hypergeometric series 2*F*1(*a*, *b*; *c*; *z*).
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The equation has two linearly independent solutions.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] At each of the three singular points 0, 1, ∞, there are usually two special solutions of the form *x**s* times a holomorphic function of *x*, where *s* is one of the two roots of the indicial equation and *x* is a local variable vanishing at a regular singular point.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] This gives 3 × 2 = 6 special solutions, as follows.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] If *c* is a non-positive integer 1 − *m*, then the first of these solutions does not exist and must be replaced by $z^{m}F(a+m,b+m;1+m;z).$ The second solution does not exist when *c* is an integer greater than 1, and is equal to the first solution, or its replacement, when *c* is any other integer.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] So when *c* is an integer, a more complicated expression must be used for a second solution, equal to the first solution multiplied by ln(*z*), plus another series in powers of *z*, involving the digamma function.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Again, when the conditions of non-integrality are not met, there exist other solutions that are more complicated.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Any 3 of the above 6 solutions satisfy a linear relation as the space of solutions is 2-dimensional, giving (6 3) = 20 linear relations between them called **connection formulas**.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] A second order Fuchsian equation with *n* singular points has a group of symmetries acting (projectively) on its solutions, isomorphic to the Coxeter group W(*D**n*) of order 2*n*−1*n*!.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The hypergeometric equation is the case *n* = 3, with group of order 24 isomorphic to the symmetric group on 4 points, as first described by Kummer.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] which correspond to the transpositions (12), (23), and (34) under an isomorphism with the symmetric group on 4 points 1, 2, 3, 4.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] by making the substitution *u* = *wv* and eliminating the first-derivative term.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The Q-form is significant in its relation to the Schwarzian derivative (Hille 1976, pp.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The **Schwarz triangle maps** or **Schwarz *s*-functions** are ratios of pairs of solutions.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Note that the connection coefficients become Möbius transformations on the triangle maps.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] In the special case of λ, μ and ν real, with 0 ≤ λ,μ,ν < 1 then the s-maps are conformal maps of the upper half-plane **H** to triangles on the Riemann sphere, bounded by circular arcs.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] This mapping is a generalization of the Schwarz–Christoffel mapping to triangles with circular arcs.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The singular points 0,1 and ∞ are sent to the triangle vertices.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The angles of the triangle are πλ, πμ and πν respectively.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The monodromy of a hypergeometric equation describes how fundamental solutions change when analytically continued around paths in the *z* plane that return to the same point.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] That is, when the path winds around a singularity of 2*F*1, the value of the solutions at the endpoint will differ from the starting point.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] In other words, the monodromy is a two dimensional linear representation of the fundamental group.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The monodromy group of the equation is the image of this map, i.e. the group generated by the monodromy matrices.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The monodromy representation of the fundamental group can be computed explicitly in terms of the exponents at the singular points.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] If 1 − *a*, *c* − *a* − *b*, *a* − *b* are non-integer rational numbers with denominators *k*, *l*, *m* then the monodromy group is finite if and only if $1/k+1/l+1/m>1$ , see Schwarz's list or Kovacic's algorithm.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] provided that *z* is not a real number such that it is greater than or equal to 1.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] This can be proved by expanding (1 − *zx*)−*a* using the binomial theorem and then integrating term by term for *z* with absolute value smaller than 1, and by analytic continuation elsewhere.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] When *z* is a real number greater than or equal to 1, analytic continuation must be used, because (1 − *zx*) is zero at some point in the support of the integral, so the value of the integral may be ill-defined.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] This was given by Euler in 1748 and implies Euler's and Pfaff's hypergeometric transformations.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Other representations, corresponding to other branches, are given by taking the same integrand, but taking the path of integration to be a closed Pochhammer cycle enclosing the singularities in various orders.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Such paths correspond to the monodromy action.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] This is valid as long as z is not a nonnegative real number.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The Gauss hypergeometric function can be written as a John transform (Gelfand, Gindikin & Graev 2003, 2.1.2).
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Gauss showed that 2*F*1(*a*, *b*; *c*; *z*) can be written as a linear combination of any two of its contiguous functions, with rational coefficients in terms of *a*, *b*, *c*, and z.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Transformation formulas relate two hypergeometric functions at different values of the argument *z*.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] For extension of Euler's first and second transformations, see Rathie & Paris (2007) and Rakha & Rathie (2011).
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] If two of the numbers 1 − *c*, *c* − 1, *a* − *b*, *b* − *a*, *a* + *b* − *c*, *c* − *a* − *b* are equal or one of them is 1/2 then there is a **quadratic transformation** of the hypergeometric function, connecting it to a different value of *z* related by a quadratic equation.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The first examples were given by Kummer (1836), and a complete list was given by Goursat (1881).
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] If 1−*c*, *a*−*b*, *a*+*b*−*c* differ by signs or two of them are 1/3 or −1/3 then there is a **cubic transformation** of the hypergeometric function, connecting it to a different value of *z* related by a cubic equation.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] The first examples were given by Goursat (1881).
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] There are also some transformations of degree 4 and 6.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Transformations of other degrees only exist if *a*, *b*, and *c* are certain rational numbers (Vidunas 2005).
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] See Slater (1966, Appendix III) for a list of summation formulas at special points, most of which also appear in Bailey (1935).
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Gessel & Stanton (1982) gives further evaluations at more points.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Koepf (1995) shows how most of these identities can be verified by computer algorithms.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] which follows from Euler's integral formula by putting *z* = 1.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] It includes the Vandermonde identity as a special case.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] Dougall's formula generalizes this to the bilateral hypergeometric series at *z* = 1.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] There are many cases where hypergeometric functions can be evaluated at *z* = −1 by using a quadratic transformation to change *z* = −1 to *z* = 1 and then using Gauss's theorem to evaluate the result.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] and Gauss's theorem by putting *z* = −1 in the first identity.
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] For generalization of Kummer's summation, see Lavoie, Grondin & Rathie (1996).
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] For generalizations of Gauss's second summation theorem and Bailey's summation theorem, see Lavoie, Grondin & Rathie (1996).
[src:special-functions/hypergeometric-function] There are many other formulas giving the hypergeometric function as an algebraic number at special rational values of the parameters, some of which are listed in Gessel & Stanton (1982) and Koepf (1995).
