[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] In mathematics, **Legendre polynomials**, named after Adrien-Marie Legendre (1782), are a system of complete and orthogonal polynomials with a wide number of mathematical properties and numerous applications.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] They can be defined in many ways, and the various definitions highlight different aspects as well as suggest generalizations and connections to different mathematical structures and physical and numerical applications.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] Closely related to the Legendre polynomials are associated Legendre polynomials, Legendre functions, Legendre functions of the second kind, big q-Legendre polynomials, and associated Legendre functions.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] In this approach, the polynomials are defined as an orthogonal system with respect to the weight function $w(x)=1$ over the interval $[-1,1]$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] With the additional standardization condition $P_{n}(1)=1$ , all the polynomials can be uniquely determined.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] This gives n conditions, which, along with the standardization $P_{n}(1)=1$ fixes all $n+1$ coefficients in $P_{n}(x)$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] With work, all the coefficients of every polynomial can be systematically determined, leading to the explicit representation in powers of x given below.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] This definition of the $P_{n}$ 's is the simplest one.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] It does not appeal to the theory of differential equations.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] Second, the completeness of the polynomials follows immediately from the completeness of the powers 1, $x,x^{2},x^{3},\ldots$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] Finally, by defining them via orthogonality with respect to the Lebesgue measure on $[-1,1]$ , it sets up the Legendre polynomials as one of the three classical orthogonal polynomial systems.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The other two are the Laguerre polynomials, which are orthogonal over the half line $[0,\infty )$ with the weight $e^{-x}$ , and the Hermite polynomials, orthogonal over the full line $(-\infty ,\infty )$ with weight $e^{-x^{2}}$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The coefficient of $t^{n}$ is a polynomial in x of degree n with $|x|\leq 1$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] Expanding up to $t^{1}$ gives $P_{0}(x)=1\,,\quad P_{1}(x)=x.$ Expansion to higher orders gets increasingly cumbersome, but is possible to do systematically, and again leads to one of the explicit forms given below.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] It is possible to obtain the higher $P_{n}$ 's without resorting to direct expansion of the Taylor series, however.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] Equation **2** is differentiated with respect to t on both sides and rearranged to obtain ${\frac {x-t}{\sqrt {1-2xt+t^{2}}}}=\left(1-2xt+t^{2}\right)\sum _{n=1}^{\infty }nP_{n}(x)t^{n-1}\,.$ Replacing the quotient of the square root with its definition in Eq.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] **2**, and equating the coefficients of powers of *t* in the resulting expansion gives *Bonnet's recursion formula* $(n+1)P_{n+1}(x)=(2n+1)xP_{n}(x)-nP_{n-1}(x)\,.$ This relation, along with the first two polynomials *P*0 and *P*1, allows all the rest to be generated recursively.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The generating function approach is directly connected to the multipole expansion in electrostatics, as explained below, and is how the polynomials were first defined by Legendre in 1782.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] This differential equation has regular singular points at *x* = ±1 so if a solution is sought using the standard Frobenius or power series method, a series about the origin will only converge for |*x*| < 1 in general.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] When *n* is an integer, the solution *Pn*(*x*) that is regular at *x* = 1 is also regular at *x* = −1, and the series for this solution terminates (i.e. it is a polynomial).
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The orthogonality and completeness of these solutions is best seen from the viewpoint of Sturm–Liouville theory.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] We rewrite the differential equation as an eigenvalue problem, ${\frac {d}{dx}}\left(\left(1-x^{2}\right){\frac {d}{dx}}P(x)\right)=-\lambda P(x)\,,$ with the eigenvalue $\lambda$ in lieu of $n(n+1)$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] This is a Sturm–Liouville equation with $p=1-x^{2},q=0,w=1$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] If we demand that the solution be regular at $x=\pm 1$ , the differential operator on the left is Hermitian.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The eigenvalues are found to be of the form *n*(*n* + 1), with $n=0,1,2,\ldots$ and the eigenfunctions are the $P_{n}(x)$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The orthogonality and completeness of this set of solutions follows at once from the larger framework of Sturm–Liouville theory.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The differential equation admits another, non-polynomial solution, the Legendre functions of the second kind $Q_{n}$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] **1**) is called Legendre's *general* differential equation, solved by the Associated Legendre polynomials.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] Legendre functions are solutions of Legendre's differential equation (generalized or not) with *non-integer* parameters.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] In physical settings, Legendre's differential equation arises naturally whenever one solves Laplace's equation (and related partial differential equations) by separation of variables in spherical coordinates.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] From this standpoint, the eigenfunctions of the angular part of the Laplacian operator are the spherical harmonics, of which the Legendre polynomials are (up to a multiplicative constant) the subset that is left invariant by rotations about the polar axis.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The polynomials appear as $P_{n}(\cos \theta )$ where $\theta$ is the polar angle.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] This approach to the Legendre polynomials provides a deep connection to rotational symmetry.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] Many of their properties which are found laboriously through the methods of analysis — for example the addition theorem — are more easily found using the methods of symmetry and group theory, and acquire profound physical and geometrical meaning.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] This formula enables derivation of a large number of properties of the $P_{n}$ 's.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The Legendre polynomial is determined by the values used for the two constants ${\textstyle a_{n,0}}$ and ${\textstyle a_{n,1}}$ , where ${\textstyle a_{n,0}=0}$ if n is odd and ${\textstyle a_{n,1}=0}$ if n is even.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] In the fourth representation, $\lfloor n/2\rfloor$ stands for the largest integer less than or equal to $n/2$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The fifth representation, which is also immediate from the recursion formula, expresses the Legendre polynomials by simple monomials and involves the generalized form of the binomial coefficient.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] for $m=0,1,2,\ldots$ , where an empty product in the numerator (last factor less than the first factor) evaluates to 1.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The standardization $P_{n}(1)=1$ fixes the normalization of the Legendre polynomials (with respect to the *L*2 norm on the interval −1 ≤ *x* ≤ 1).
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] That the polynomials are complete means the following.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] This completeness property underlies all the expansions discussed in this article, and is often stated in the form $\sum _{\ell =0}^{\infty }{\frac {2\ell +1}{2}}P_{\ell }(x)P_{\ell }(y)=\delta (x-y),$ with −1 ≤ *x* ≤ 1 and −1 ≤ *y* ≤ 1.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The expression gives the gravitational potential associated to a point mass or the Coulomb potential associated to a point charge.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The expansion using Legendre polynomials might be useful, for instance, when integrating this expression over a continuous mass or charge distribution.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] Legendre polynomials occur in the solution of Laplace's equation of the static potential, ∇2 Φ(**x**) = 0, in a charge-free region of space, using the method of separation of variables, where the boundary conditions have axial symmetry (no dependence on an azimuthal angle).
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] They also appear when solving the Schrödinger equation in three dimensions for a central force.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] Legendre polynomials are also useful in expanding functions of the form (this is the same as before, written a little differently): ${\frac {1}{\sqrt {1+\eta ^{2}-2\eta x}}}=\sum _{k=0}^{\infty }\eta ^{k}P_{k}(x),$ which arise naturally in multipole expansions.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The left-hand side of the equation is the generating function for the Legendre polynomials.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] If the radius *r* of the observation point P is greater than *a*, the potential may be expanded in the Legendre polynomials $\Phi (r,\theta )\propto {\frac {1}{r}}\sum _{k=0}^{\infty }\left({\frac {a}{r}}\right)^{k}P_{k}(\cos \theta ),$ where we have defined *η* = ⁠*a*/*r*⁠ < 1 and *x* = cos *θ*.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] This expansion is used to develop the normal multipole expansion.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] Conversely, if the radius *r* of the observation point P is smaller than *a*, the potential may still be expanded in the Legendre polynomials as above, but with *a* and *r* exchanged.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] This expansion is the basis of interior multipole expansion.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The trigonometric functions cos *nθ*, also denoted as the Chebyshev polynomials *Tn*(cos *θ*) ≡ cos *nθ*, can also be multipole expanded by the Legendre polynomials *Pn*(cos *θ*).
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] where ${\hat {n}}\equiv \lfloor n/2\rfloor$ , $n'\equiv \lfloor (n+1)/2\rfloor$ , and where the products with the steps of two in the numerator and denominator are to be interpreted as 1 if they are empty, i.e., if the last factor is smaller than the first factor.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] When combined with deep learning methods, these networks can be trained to outperform long short-term memory units and related architectures, while using fewer computational resources.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] Legendre polynomials have definite parity.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] Another useful property is $\int _{-1}^{1}P_{n}(x)\,dx=0,\quad n\geq 1,$ which follows from considering the orthogonality relation with $P_{0}(x)=1$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] It is convenient when a Legendre series ${\textstyle \sum _{i}a_{i}P_{i}}$ is used to approximate a function or experimental data: the *average* of the series over the interval [−1, 1] is simply given by the leading expansion coefficient $a_{0}$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] All n zeros of $P_{n}(x)$ are real, distinct from each other, and lie in the interval $(-1,1)$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] Furthermore, if we regard them as dividing the interval $[-1,1]$ into $n+1$ subintervals, each subinterval will contain exactly one zero of $P_{n+1}$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] This is known as the interlacing property.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] Because of the parity property it is evident that if $x_{k}$ is a zero of $P_{n}(x)$ , so is $-x_{k}$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] These zeros play an important role in numerical integration based on Gaussian quadrature.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The specific quadrature based on the $P_{n}$ 's is known as Gauss-Legendre quadrature.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] This can be proved by looking at the first formula of Dirichlet-Mehler.
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] From this property and the facts that $P_{n}(\pm 1)\neq 0$ , it follows that $P_{n}(x)$ has $n-1$ local minima and maxima in $(-1,1)$ .
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] The Legendre rational functions are a sequence of orthogonal functions on [0, ∞).
[src:special-functions/legendre-polynomials] They are obtained by composing the Cayley transform with Legendre polynomials.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] The term is defined by consensus, and thus lacks a general formal definition, but the list of mathematical functions contains functions that are commonly accepted as special.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Many special functions appear as solutions of differential equations or integrals of elementary functions.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Therefore, tables of integrals usually include descriptions of special functions, and tables of special functions include most important integrals; at least, the integral representation of special functions.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Because symmetries of differential equations are essential to both physics and mathematics, the theory of special functions is closely related to the theory of Lie groups and Lie algebras, as well as certain topics in mathematical physics.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Symbolic computation engines usually recognize the majority of special functions.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Functions with established international notations are the sine ( $\sin$ ), cosine ( $\cos$ ), exponential function ( $\exp$ ), and error function ( $\operatorname {erf}$ or $\operatorname {erfc}$ ).
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Subscripts are often used to indicate arguments, typically integers.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] In a few cases, the semicolon (;) or even backslash (\) is used as a separator for arguments.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] This may confuse the translation to algorithmic languages.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Superscripts may indicate not only a power (exponent), but some other modification of the function.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Most special functions are considered as a function of a complex variable.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] They are analytic; the singularities and cuts are described; the differential and integral representations are known and the expansion to the Taylor series or asymptotic series are available.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] In addition, sometimes there exist relations with other special functions; a complicated special function can be expressed in terms of simpler functions.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Various representations can be used for the evaluation; the simplest way to evaluate a function is to expand it into a Taylor series.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] However, such representation may converge slowly or not at all.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] In algorithmic languages, rational approximations are typically used, although they may behave badly in the case of complex argument(s).
[src:special-functions/special-functions] While trigonometry and exponential functions were systematized and unified by the eighteenth century, the search for a complete and unified theory of special functions has continued since the nineteenth century.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] The high point of special function theory in 1800–1900 was the theory of elliptic functions; treatises that were essentially complete, such as that of Tannery and Molk, expounded all the basic identities of the theory using techniques from analytic function theory (based on complex analysis).
[src:special-functions/special-functions] The end of the century also saw a very detailed discussion of spherical harmonics.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] While pure mathematicians sought a broad theory deriving as many as possible of the known special functions from a single principle, for a long time the special functions were the province of applied mathematics.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Applications to the physical sciences and engineering determined the relative importance of functions.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Before electronic computation, the importance of a special function was affirmed by the laborious computation of extended tables of values for ready look-up, as for the familiar logarithm tables.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] More theoretical questions include: asymptotic analysis; analytic continuation and monodromy in the complex plane; and symmetry principles and other structural equations.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] The twentieth century saw several waves of interest in special function theory.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] The classic *Whittaker and Watson* (1902) textbook sought to unify the theory using complex analysis; the G.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Watson tome *A Treatise on the Theory of Bessel Functions* pushed the techniques as far as possible for one important type, including asymptotic results.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] The later Bateman Manuscript Project, under the editorship of Arthur Erdélyi, attempted to be encyclopedic, and came around the time when electronic computation was coming to the fore and tabulation ceased to be the main issue.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] The modern theory of orthogonal polynomials is of a definite but limited scope.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Hypergeometric series, observed by Felix Klein to be important in astronomy and mathematical physics, became an intricate theory, requiring later conceptual arrangement.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Lie group representations give an immediate generalization of spherical functions; from 1950 onwards substantial parts of classical theory were recast in terms of Lie groups.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Further, work on algebraic combinatorics also revived interest in older parts of the theory.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Macdonald helped open up large and active new fields with a special function flavour.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Difference equations have begun to take their place beside differential equations as a source of special functions.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] In number theory, certain special functions have traditionally been studied, such as particular Dirichlet series and modular forms.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Almost all aspects of special function theory are reflected there, as well as some new ones, such as came out of monstrous moonshine theory.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] Analogues of several special functions have been defined on the space of positive definite matrices, among them the power function which goes back to Atle Selberg, the multivariate gamma function, and types of Bessel functions.
[src:special-functions/special-functions] The NIST Digital Library of Mathematical Functions has a section covering several special functions of matrix arguments.
